WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.380
And how Parliament makes the law.

2
00:00:01.545 --> 00:00:04.565
So leg legislative scrutiny, legislative quality,

3
00:00:04.945 --> 00:00:07.565
and legit legitimacy of the law making process.

4
00:00:08.305 --> 00:00:11.565
Um, it's fair to say the house's ability to deal with

5
00:00:11.565 --> 00:00:13.845
and thoroughly scrutinized bills is being affected

6
00:00:13.865 --> 00:00:16.605
by growing pressures on time, pressures on time

7
00:00:16.665 --> 00:00:17.885
for members and for the house.

8
00:00:18.545 --> 00:00:21.765
Um, and so focused on trying to present ideas

9
00:00:21.825 --> 00:00:24.045
for discussion rather than solutions.

10
00:00:24.245 --> 00:00:28.045
Although there are some ideas, um, in there about solutions.

11
00:00:28.465 --> 00:00:31.485
Um, really the first step I think would be to achieve, uh,

12
00:00:31.485 --> 00:00:33.205
an understanding across the committee and

13
00:00:33.205 --> 00:00:35.365
therefore across parties, um, about

14
00:00:35.365 --> 00:00:38.125
what good lawmaking would look like to assess

15
00:00:38.205 --> 00:00:39.685
what we're currently doing against that.

16
00:00:40.145 --> 00:00:42.845
And then if there are gaps to figure out, uh, how

17
00:00:42.845 --> 00:00:43.925
to, how to plug those.

18
00:00:44.565 --> 00:00:46.805
I think just in starting and say the submission doesn't seek

19
00:00:46.805 --> 00:00:48.925
to criticize particular members or parties

20
00:00:49.425 --> 00:00:50.765
or committees, um,

21
00:00:50.945 --> 00:00:53.205
it really is looking at the system we've got now, um,

22
00:00:53.305 --> 00:00:55.325
and raising some questions about whether there

23
00:00:55.325 --> 00:00:56.405
are things we could do better.

24
00:00:57.065 --> 00:00:59.895
Um, the question here is really whether the rules

25
00:00:59.895 --> 00:01:02.335
and practice of the house in their current form, um,

26
00:01:02.565 --> 00:01:05.095
promote good legislative and democratic outcomes.

27
00:01:05.355 --> 00:01:06.855
And I don't think that's always the case.

28
00:01:08.355 --> 00:01:10.975
So with that, by introduction, uh, by way of introduction,

29
00:01:11.295 --> 00:01:13.215
I think when we are thinking about the legislative system,

30
00:01:13.715 --> 00:01:16.295
um, obviously we think about the part that the House

31
00:01:16.295 --> 00:01:18.575
of Representatives plays as, uh,

32
00:01:18.635 --> 00:01:20.215
the main lawmaking body along

33
00:01:20.215 --> 00:01:22.055
with the governor general forming Parliament.

34
00:01:22.555 --> 00:01:25.135
Um, but there are, there is a wider system.

35
00:01:25.315 --> 00:01:28.335
Uh, policy development is obviously done by the executive.

36
00:01:28.675 --> 00:01:30.535
Um, implementation is done by the executive

37
00:01:30.535 --> 00:01:34.015
and so is stewardship of, uh, of legislation.

38
00:01:34.105 --> 00:01:37.535
Parliament also delegates its powers to make laws, uh,

39
00:01:37.555 --> 00:01:40.375
to ministers and to other public authorities as well.

40
00:01:40.595 --> 00:01:43.055
Of course, the judiciary interprets it, um,

41
00:01:43.195 --> 00:01:45.895
and every part of the system is affected by the other parts.

42
00:01:46.515 --> 00:01:48.495
What's really relevant to this submission is the part

43
00:01:48.495 --> 00:01:51.375
that the house's rules and practices play in

44
00:01:51.595 --> 00:01:54.815
how effective the law making by Parliament is.

45
00:01:56.565 --> 00:01:58.625
Uh, just to set a bit more context,

46
00:01:58.885 --> 00:02:00.265
as you know, we have no upper house.

47
00:02:00.765 --> 00:02:02.185
The parliament is unicameral,

48
00:02:02.185 --> 00:02:05.545
and so there is no second body to pause, revise,

49
00:02:05.545 --> 00:02:07.025
or raise concerns about legislation.

50
00:02:07.125 --> 00:02:09.145
It is entirely on the House of Representatives,

51
00:02:09.275 --> 00:02:11.185
which makes it possible to make laws very quickly.

52
00:02:11.645 --> 00:02:12.905
But also I think, um,

53
00:02:13.175 --> 00:02:15.065
creates a particular emphasis on the role

54
00:02:15.065 --> 00:02:16.185
that select committees play.

55
00:02:16.485 --> 00:02:18.385
Um, 'cause that is the only place for revision.

56
00:02:19.085 --> 00:02:22.065
The three year electoral cycle is also, um, short

57
00:02:22.065 --> 00:02:23.185
by international standards.

58
00:02:24.295 --> 00:02:27.065
Generally, parliament's, uh, terms are about 50% longer,

59
00:02:27.065 --> 00:02:29.865
more like four and a half years on average around the world.

60
00:02:30.365 --> 00:02:34.145
The short term places stress on, uh, the government

61
00:02:34.285 --> 00:02:36.505
to develop its policy, um,

62
00:02:36.765 --> 00:02:39.225
and on drafters to draft legislation.

63
00:02:39.765 --> 00:02:42.025
Um, it affects the timeframes available to the house

64
00:02:42.025 --> 00:02:43.065
to legislate as well.

65
00:02:43.685 --> 00:02:47.305
And, um, so there is quite a time pressure, um,

66
00:02:47.305 --> 00:02:50.105
which I think we see, you know, reflected in the speed

67
00:02:50.105 --> 00:02:52.345
with which Laura is sometimes made. I don't want

68
00:02:52.345 --> 00:02:54.065
Interrupt Flow. That's all right. But,

69
00:02:54.995 --> 00:02:58.975
Um, something that I've observed is that, um,

70
00:02:59.955 --> 00:03:02.205
most of those parliaments have a longer

71
00:03:02.205 --> 00:03:03.645
term, do have an upper house.

72
00:03:03.645 --> 00:03:07.925
Mm-hmm. So there is a natural, um, break to proceedings.

73
00:03:07.985 --> 00:03:11.405
How many are you aware of that with a three year term?

74
00:03:11.675 --> 00:03:13.085
Also have an upper house?

75
00:03:13.995 --> 00:03:16.325
There's a very small number with a three year term.

76
00:03:16.405 --> 00:03:17.925
I think we could find that out quite easily.

77
00:03:18.145 --> 00:03:19.605
Um, I dunno off the off of my head,

78
00:03:19.625 --> 00:03:21.685
but we're talking about a hand, literally a handful

79
00:03:21.705 --> 00:03:23.125
of parliaments that have a three year

80
00:03:23.125 --> 00:03:24.725
term. So yeah, Australia.

81
00:03:25.235 --> 00:03:28.485
Yeah, no, my point was, uh, how many of those,

82
00:03:29.225 --> 00:03:31.405
how many parliaments have three years in just

83
00:03:31.425 --> 00:03:32.605
one uni camera house?

84
00:03:33.675 --> 00:03:35.765
I'll come back to you. I dunno that answer. Thank you.

85
00:03:36.865 --> 00:03:38.645
But un under the Westminster model, um,

86
00:03:38.965 --> 00:03:41.125
emphasis on placed on having an opposition, um,

87
00:03:41.515 --> 00:03:44.165
that can scrutinize, can critique the government.

88
00:03:44.665 --> 00:03:48.085
Um, and the standing orders are, you know, to facilitate

89
00:03:48.085 --> 00:03:49.685
and foster that debate and criticism.

90
00:03:49.945 --> 00:03:51.885
The Parliament isn't supposed to be efficient in terms

91
00:03:51.885 --> 00:03:53.125
of achieving things as quickly

92
00:03:53.145 --> 00:03:54.925
as possible at the lowest possible cost.

93
00:03:55.345 --> 00:03:56.725
It is supposed to be effective.

94
00:03:57.105 --> 00:03:59.405
And really to be effective, it's gotta strike a balance

95
00:03:59.405 --> 00:04:01.845
between the legitimate right of the government

96
00:04:01.845 --> 00:04:04.405
to implement its policy program that was elected for.

97
00:04:04.785 --> 00:04:06.965
Um, but also the role of non-government parties

98
00:04:07.025 --> 00:04:08.805
and back bench, bench bench members,

99
00:04:08.805 --> 00:04:12.605
generally in scrutinizing the lawmaking that has done.

100
00:04:14.505 --> 00:04:16.585
I think another important part of the context is

101
00:04:16.735 --> 00:04:18.705
that governments have a stable

102
00:04:18.725 --> 00:04:20.905
and reliable majority in the house in New Zealand,

103
00:04:21.235 --> 00:04:23.265
which means procedural decisions can be

104
00:04:23.265 --> 00:04:24.545
reliably made by the government.

105
00:04:24.785 --> 00:04:28.865
Decisions like taking urgency, uh, closure motions, um,

106
00:04:29.365 --> 00:04:31.625
and extended sittings instructions

107
00:04:31.625 --> 00:04:33.545
to silly committees are all things the government can

108
00:04:33.545 --> 00:04:35.065
generally rely on doing.

109
00:04:35.325 --> 00:04:38.145
So it's up to the house's own procedural settings

110
00:04:38.925 --> 00:04:41.465
to achieve a balance, um, both in terms of

111
00:04:41.465 --> 00:04:42.505
what the government wants to achieve,

112
00:04:42.605 --> 00:04:44.185
but also what the house as a whole might

113
00:04:44.365 --> 00:04:45.465
and making good law.

114
00:04:47.105 --> 00:04:49.565
It appears to me that the current procedural settings are

115
00:04:49.565 --> 00:04:52.085
placing some pressure on the legislative system,

116
00:04:52.785 --> 00:04:55.125
and I, I think there's a good case for adjusting some

117
00:04:55.125 --> 00:04:57.485
of those, and I'll set those out in a bit more detail.

118
00:04:57.865 --> 00:05:00.885
Before I do just mention the role of the legislation design

119
00:05:00.885 --> 00:05:03.285
and advisory committee, the LDAC, um,

120
00:05:03.285 --> 00:05:04.325
which is an expert group.

121
00:05:04.325 --> 00:05:05.845
It's appointed by the Attorney General

122
00:05:06.185 --> 00:05:07.765
to promote quality legislation.

123
00:05:07.945 --> 00:05:11.045
So while it was part of the executive, um, it is important

124
00:05:11.045 --> 00:05:12.485
to the whole legislative system

125
00:05:12.595 --> 00:05:14.405
because it gives advice on design

126
00:05:14.465 --> 00:05:16.805
and framework, constitutional and public law issues.

127
00:05:17.425 --> 00:05:21.765
And it, um, has, uh, some core objectives that it describes

128
00:05:21.765 --> 00:05:24.285
as, as, you know, belonging to legislation three,

129
00:05:24.475 --> 00:05:26.685
that it should be fit for purpose, uh,

130
00:05:26.685 --> 00:05:28.325
that should be constitutionally sound,

131
00:05:28.585 --> 00:05:31.045
and it should be accessible, able to be, you know, found

132
00:05:31.065 --> 00:05:32.405
and understood and navigated.

133
00:05:33.025 --> 00:05:35.045
So I think those objectives are good ones,

134
00:05:35.345 --> 00:05:37.605
but they're expressed in terms of the product, the sort

135
00:05:37.605 --> 00:05:39.725
of the result of the making of law.

136
00:05:40.325 --> 00:05:43.365
I think the quality of the process is what matters as well,

137
00:05:43.635 --> 00:05:47.765
because that gives, um, the balances those, uh,

138
00:05:48.265 --> 00:05:50.005
rights of both government and opposition.

139
00:05:50.065 --> 00:05:52.045
It gives public legitimacy, uh,

140
00:05:52.045 --> 00:05:54.725
to law making if people can have confidence in the process.

141
00:05:54.745 --> 00:05:58.285
That's followed. And, uh, there's a useful, um, piece

142
00:05:58.285 --> 00:06:01.645
of writing on this that was, um, done in 2011

143
00:06:01.645 --> 00:06:03.765
and fed into the standing orders review at the time.

144
00:06:04.185 --> 00:06:07.125
Uh, it was written by Claudia Inger, Polly Higby

145
00:06:07.125 --> 00:06:09.045
and Elizabeth McClean, it was called, what's the Hurry?

146
00:06:09.665 --> 00:06:12.485
Um, and they actually articulated some quite useful

147
00:06:12.485 --> 00:06:17.245
principles, um, I think about how lawmaking should be done.

148
00:06:17.505 --> 00:06:19.605
So they suggested it should be an informed

149
00:06:19.865 --> 00:06:21.525
and open policy deliberation.

150
00:06:22.145 --> 00:06:24.125
Uh, there should be adequate scrutiny of bills.

151
00:06:24.965 --> 00:06:26.365
Citizens should be able to participate.

152
00:06:26.695 --> 00:06:28.845
Parliament should operate in a transparent manner.

153
00:06:29.665 --> 00:06:32.005
Uh, they should try and produce high quality legislation.

154
00:06:32.955 --> 00:06:35.325
Legislation shouldn't jeopardize fundamental

155
00:06:35.685 --> 00:06:36.885
constitutional rights and principles.

156
00:06:37.255 --> 00:06:39.845
Parliament should follow stable procedural rules.

157
00:06:40.355 --> 00:06:42.325
They should foster and rather erode,

158
00:06:42.345 --> 00:06:45.485
rather than erode respect for themselves as an institution.

159
00:06:46.065 --> 00:06:47.885
The government has a right to govern so long

160
00:06:47.885 --> 00:06:48.885
as it's got a majority in the house,

161
00:06:49.265 --> 00:06:51.645
but also Parliament should be able

162
00:06:51.645 --> 00:06:54.845
to enact legislation in an emergency very quickly.

163
00:06:55.745 --> 00:06:57.925
Um, and so I, I think they're quite a good basis

164
00:06:58.025 --> 00:06:59.885
for thinking about how our, you know,

165
00:06:59.885 --> 00:07:01.845
lawmaking process is going.

166
00:07:05.415 --> 00:07:07.815
Parliament's constantly passing rules,

167
00:07:08.395 --> 00:07:10.415
but there's also an important role

168
00:07:10.415 --> 00:07:13.375
for the public service in legislative stewardship, um,

169
00:07:14.455 --> 00:07:16.215
identifying legislation that needs updating.

170
00:07:16.635 --> 00:07:19.135
And there's an inherent tension, uh, for the house

171
00:07:19.195 --> 00:07:20.495
and particularly for ministers.

172
00:07:20.495 --> 00:07:21.935
And I think particularly for the leader

173
00:07:21.935 --> 00:07:25.055
of the house in managing the need to kind

174
00:07:25.055 --> 00:07:26.375
of move on those machinery

175
00:07:26.375 --> 00:07:29.895
of government update type legislation with the need

176
00:07:29.895 --> 00:07:31.575
to deliver on the government's policy program.

177
00:07:32.195 --> 00:07:35.415
And that creates a real tension in finding time to do both

178
00:07:35.415 --> 00:07:37.455
of those things in the house.

179
00:07:38.995 --> 00:07:41.235
I would say though, that regardless of

180
00:07:41.235 --> 00:07:43.315
that legislation is always going

181
00:07:43.315 --> 00:07:45.195
to be better if it's been developed fully

182
00:07:45.195 --> 00:07:46.195
before it's brought to the house.

183
00:07:46.855 --> 00:07:48.475
That's gonna result in better law.

184
00:07:48.625 --> 00:07:50.315
When policy hasn't been fully settled

185
00:07:50.335 --> 00:07:52.395
before a bill's introduced, you're likely

186
00:07:52.455 --> 00:07:56.075
to see substantive policy changes at select committee, um,

187
00:07:56.535 --> 00:07:58.555
rather than refinement of the law.

188
00:07:59.055 --> 00:08:02.035
Uh, and you also even less desirable are likely

189
00:08:02.035 --> 00:08:03.315
to see a committee of the whole house.

190
00:08:03.815 --> 00:08:06.315
So I think it would be worth thinking in this review about

191
00:08:06.315 --> 00:08:10.035
whether there are incentives that could encourage, uh,

192
00:08:10.315 --> 00:08:11.875
ministers, particularly because they're in charge

193
00:08:11.875 --> 00:08:15.795
of almost all bills, um, to, to, to take that time

194
00:08:15.905 --> 00:08:19.155
with the departments to develop policy fully in every case.

195
00:08:19.325 --> 00:08:21.195
Maybe there are some incentives for doing that,

196
00:08:24.635 --> 00:08:27.975
And there are pressures you all know on you as lawmakers

197
00:08:28.195 --> 00:08:30.055
and on people that support you in this place.

198
00:08:30.055 --> 00:08:31.895
And, and those are the things I wanna focus on in the next

199
00:08:31.895 --> 00:08:32.695
couple of parts of the

200
00:08:32.695 --> 00:08:34.135
submission and the written submission.

201
00:08:34.135 --> 00:08:35.255
That's parts two and three.

202
00:08:35.755 --> 00:08:37.535
Um, there's a huge workload demand

203
00:08:37.885 --> 00:08:41.295
that arises from active engagement in legis, in legislating.

204
00:08:41.675 --> 00:08:44.615
And I, I think if we're considering reforms, we need

205
00:08:44.615 --> 00:08:47.175
to make sure that at, at the very least, we're not making

206
00:08:47.175 --> 00:08:49.615
that more difficult, but ideally we are making it a bit

207
00:08:49.615 --> 00:08:50.895
easier and lifting that

208
00:08:50.895 --> 00:08:52.375
lightning, that workload a little bit.

209
00:08:54.695 --> 00:08:56.155
So if it comes first to the house

210
00:08:56.495 --> 00:09:00.475
and, um, committee of the whole house procedures start

211
00:09:00.475 --> 00:09:02.635
by saying the time of the house is a limited resource,

212
00:09:02.895 --> 00:09:05.835
and its allocation is a matter of constitutional importance

213
00:09:05.945 --> 00:09:08.955
because it influences the capacity

214
00:09:08.955 --> 00:09:10.875
and the quality of the state's lawmaking ability.

215
00:09:11.735 --> 00:09:13.755
Um, at each review of standing orders,

216
00:09:13.855 --> 00:09:16.755
we consider whether the settings in, in the rules

217
00:09:16.775 --> 00:09:18.115
and practices of the house are right.

218
00:09:18.775 --> 00:09:20.955
Um, and, and I think there's a really good opportunity to do

219
00:09:20.955 --> 00:09:23.075
that in, in terms of how Parliament makes the law.

220
00:09:23.735 --> 00:09:26.515
So normal sitting hours are 17 a week, uh,

221
00:09:26.515 --> 00:09:27.595
for 28 weeks a year.

222
00:09:27.975 --> 00:09:30.955
Uh, and I just apologize, uh, in the, um, on page 18

223
00:09:30.975 --> 00:09:33.955
of the written submission, I've said 17.5 hours,

224
00:09:34.255 --> 00:09:35.435
uh, that's a, a typo.

225
00:09:35.435 --> 00:09:38.075
It's just 17 hours. No, we we're not missing half an hour.

226
00:09:38.895 --> 00:09:41.155
Um, governments can access additional hours

227
00:09:41.155 --> 00:09:43.195
through extended sittings and through urgency,

228
00:09:43.455 --> 00:09:44.755
but frequent use of those,

229
00:09:45.115 --> 00:09:47.435
I think does create another set of problems.

230
00:09:48.175 --> 00:09:50.055
So in terms of urgency,

231
00:09:50.085 --> 00:09:51.695
there's two main effects, as you know.

232
00:09:52.115 --> 00:09:54.415
Uh, the first is that, you know, business can be progressed

233
00:09:54.415 --> 00:09:56.575
through multiple stages in the same sitting day.

234
00:09:57.075 --> 00:09:59.735
And also that the sitting continues until either all

235
00:09:59.735 --> 00:10:01.615
of the urgent business is done, uh,

236
00:10:01.675 --> 00:10:03.135
or the government decides it doesn't want

237
00:10:03.135 --> 00:10:04.135
to make more progress.

238
00:10:04.475 --> 00:10:06.175
Or in, you know, extreme cases,

239
00:10:06.175 --> 00:10:07.375
we reach midnight on a Saturday

240
00:10:07.435 --> 00:10:08.695
and the house has to adjourn.

241
00:10:09.365 --> 00:10:12.055
There's no procedural threshold for urgency.

242
00:10:12.715 --> 00:10:16.015
Um, the minister is required to give reasons for urgency

243
00:10:16.015 --> 00:10:18.335
with some particularity, but there is no decision

244
00:10:18.355 --> 00:10:20.375
to be made apart from a vote on

245
00:10:20.375 --> 00:10:21.495
whether to have urgency or not.

246
00:10:21.675 --> 00:10:23.735
As I said, governments always have a majority

247
00:10:23.735 --> 00:10:25.015
they can rely on to do that.

248
00:10:26.095 --> 00:10:29.035
And clearly there has to be a mechanism for laws to be able

249
00:10:29.035 --> 00:10:32.195
to be passed quickly to deal with immediate situations

250
00:10:32.195 --> 00:10:33.235
that are genuinely urgent.

251
00:10:33.465 --> 00:10:34.795
That happens from time to time.

252
00:10:35.695 --> 00:10:37.875
But on the other hand, it's not always apparent

253
00:10:38.255 --> 00:10:39.315
why urgency is needed.

254
00:10:39.455 --> 00:10:41.475
And, you know, ministers, uh,

255
00:10:41.655 --> 00:10:43.875
across successive governments make no secret the fact

256
00:10:43.905 --> 00:10:47.475
that often it is just used to progress the, uh,

257
00:10:47.575 --> 00:10:48.915
the government's legislative program.

258
00:10:49.775 --> 00:10:52.075
Um, and that might be an indicator that, uh,

