They're obviously not, uh, you know, sufficient, uh,

514
00:21:43.245 --> 00:21:44.325
incentive to do that.

515
00:21:44.425 --> 00:21:46.405
But I, I do think it's worth thinking about whether

516
00:21:47.225 --> 00:21:50.125
the rules around single subject areas could be relaxed a

517
00:21:50.125 --> 00:21:53.125
little bit in on a case by case basis as an incentive.

518
00:21:55.315 --> 00:21:57.975
Um, one of the thing I think is quite closely related

519
00:21:57.975 --> 00:22:02.535
to extended sittings and, um, urgency is the use

520
00:22:02.535 --> 00:22:04.055
of instructions to select committees.

521
00:22:04.435 --> 00:22:06.615
Um, so the procedure for instructions

522
00:22:06.615 --> 00:22:08.015
to select committees is an old one.

523
00:22:08.515 --> 00:22:13.215
Uh, in 1979, the norm of all of, of all builds,

524
00:22:13.215 --> 00:22:14.895
generally going to committees was established.

525
00:22:15.195 --> 00:22:17.455
Um, the procedure for instructions is older than that.

526
00:22:17.995 --> 00:22:20.775
And until 2011, uh, instructions

527
00:22:20.775 --> 00:22:22.455
to committees always moved without debate.

528
00:22:23.195 --> 00:22:25.575
Um, the standing orders committee at the time was concerned

529
00:22:25.575 --> 00:22:28.535
about that, that it could see the fore shortening

530
00:22:28.555 --> 00:22:31.975
of select committee consideration of bills routinely, uh,

531
00:22:31.975 --> 00:22:33.615
because there was no time penalty

532
00:22:33.755 --> 00:22:35.095
for the government to pay for doing that.

533
00:22:35.435 --> 00:22:38.015
And so, um, it was going to recommend

534
00:22:38.285 --> 00:22:41.055
that all instructions be debatable, all instructions

535
00:22:41.055 --> 00:22:42.495
to select committees be debatable.

536
00:22:42.665 --> 00:22:44.655
There wasn't universal agreement about that.

537
00:22:44.655 --> 00:22:48.135
And so the compromise was that if the only instruction is

538
00:22:48.135 --> 00:22:49.855
to shorten the reporting date between four

539
00:22:49.855 --> 00:22:51.975
and six months, it not be debatable.

540
00:22:52.555 --> 00:22:53.855
Um, the standing orders committee

541
00:22:53.885 --> 00:22:55.015
also said there's no intention.

542
00:22:55.075 --> 00:22:58.495
The default period for select committee consideration should

543
00:22:58.495 --> 00:23:00.615
be shortened, and the government should exercise due

544
00:23:00.615 --> 00:23:02.535
constraint when considering the tation

545
00:23:02.955 --> 00:23:04.215
of the select committee process.

546
00:23:05.115 --> 00:23:07.295
So, you know, while the six month period

547
00:23:07.955 --> 00:23:10.735
of consideration is the default, only a minority

548
00:23:10.735 --> 00:23:13.255
of bills over the last couple of parliament, um,

549
00:23:13.255 --> 00:23:14.575
have actually benefited from that.

550
00:23:14.755 --> 00:23:16.975
Uh, and I do genuinely mean a minority.

551
00:23:16.985 --> 00:23:19.415
44% were referred to committees

552
00:23:19.415 --> 00:23:21.095
for the default six month period.

553
00:23:21.835 --> 00:23:23.495
Um, and there's a breakdown

554
00:23:23.495 --> 00:23:25.695
of statistics on page 28 of the submission.

555
00:23:25.995 --> 00:23:30.255
Um, so 44% went for six months, 22% went for between four

556
00:23:30.255 --> 00:23:33.455
and six months, 13% went for four months or less,

557
00:23:33.475 --> 00:23:36.215
and 20%, as I mentioned previously, didn't go at all

558
00:23:36.215 --> 00:23:38.615
because they asked, uh, through under urgency.

559
00:23:40.165 --> 00:23:42.905
The select committee system in New Zealand is widely

560
00:23:42.905 --> 00:23:44.625
acknowledged as being a, a, you know,

561
00:23:44.625 --> 00:23:46.005
a successful and effective one.

562
00:23:46.265 --> 00:23:48.085
Um, select committees are often called the workhorse

563
00:23:48.085 --> 00:23:51.365
of parliament because of the volume of quality work they do.

564
00:23:52.065 --> 00:23:54.845
Uh, and because of the, you know, direct engagement

565
00:23:54.845 --> 00:23:57.925
with the public, the current procedure doesn't achi appear

566
00:23:57.925 --> 00:24:02.285
to be achieving, uh, that purpose where only now minority

567
00:24:02.285 --> 00:24:03.405
of bills are going to a committee

568
00:24:03.625 --> 00:24:04.725
for, for that period of time.

569
00:24:05.265 --> 00:24:08.845
So one potential change would be that all instructions

570
00:24:08.845 --> 00:24:11.485
to select committees, again, be debatable, uh,

571
00:24:11.665 --> 00:24:15.285
to put a constraint on shortening select committee, consider

572
00:24:15.805 --> 00:24:18.205
consideration of bills in all, but the most important cases.

573
00:24:22.275 --> 00:24:26.105
Um, I've discussed

574
00:24:26.105 --> 00:24:29.385
how bills can undergo substantial policy change during

575
00:24:30.105 --> 00:24:31.185
consideration by select committee

576
00:24:31.245 --> 00:24:32.385
or in committee of the whole house

577
00:24:32.385 --> 00:24:34.825
where the policy hasn't been fully fleshed out Before

578
00:24:35.105 --> 00:24:37.905
introduction, there's been a growing practice

579
00:24:37.925 --> 00:24:40.425
of proposing substantive policy changes at committee

580
00:24:40.425 --> 00:24:43.705
of the whole, whole house stage that's been recognized

581
00:24:43.705 --> 00:24:45.145
as a problem for quite a long time.

582
00:24:45.215 --> 00:24:46.625
It's, it's not new.

583
00:24:47.085 --> 00:24:48.705
Uh, as far back as 1995,

584
00:24:48.725 --> 00:24:51.025
the standing orders committee was urging that amendments

585
00:24:51.025 --> 00:24:53.185
that made substantive change should go

586
00:24:53.185 --> 00:24:54.745
to select committees for consideration.

587
00:24:55.205 --> 00:24:57.225
In 2011, the Standing Orders Committee said,

588
00:24:57.355 --> 00:25:00.305
major policy changes can be made to build a little warning

589
00:25:00.445 --> 00:25:01.785
and without sufficient scrutiny.

590
00:25:02.685 --> 00:25:06.425
Uh, in 2017, the committee reiterated it was good practice

591
00:25:06.445 --> 00:25:08.745
for substantive amendments to go to select committees,

592
00:25:09.205 --> 00:25:13.345
and in 2020, um, the house changed the standing orders to,

593
00:25:13.345 --> 00:25:14.745
to make that easier to occur.

594
00:25:15.765 --> 00:25:20.725
Um, I think the substantive alteration of the policy

595
00:25:21.105 --> 00:25:22.805
of a bill at the committee stage

596
00:25:22.805 --> 00:25:23.885
was very late in the process.

597
00:25:24.785 --> 00:25:26.285
Um, remains an issue

598
00:25:26.285 --> 00:25:28.325
that warrants some consideration by this committee.

599
00:25:28.945 --> 00:25:33.365
Um, and I, I don't propose, um, setting,

600
00:25:33.745 --> 00:25:36.565
uh, a specific procedural consequence for it,

601
00:25:36.565 --> 00:25:40.245
but one possibility would be that the committee articulates

602
00:25:40.245 --> 00:25:42.845
that we're a, uh, we, a,

603
00:25:43.065 --> 00:25:45.845
an amendment paper contains substantive amendments, um,

604
00:25:45.945 --> 00:25:47.685
and it's introduced at committee of the whole house.

605
00:25:47.835 --> 00:25:49.205
That is a fact to the chairperson

606
00:25:49.205 --> 00:25:51.325
and committee of the whole house would take into account

607
00:25:51.325 --> 00:25:53.685
when considering whether to accept a closure or not.

608
00:25:55.015 --> 00:25:58.865
Related to that, um, is the late release of amendment papers

609
00:25:59.365 --> 00:26:02.465
or what used to be called supplementary order papers, um,

610
00:26:02.965 --> 00:26:04.865
the majority of them are being released,

611
00:26:05.085 --> 00:26:06.425
and they have been over the last couple

612
00:26:06.425 --> 00:26:08.345
of parliaments one day or less

613
00:26:08.925 --> 00:26:09.945
before the committee

614
00:26:09.945 --> 00:26:11.585
of the whole house, to which they relate.

615
00:26:15.965 --> 00:26:17.705
So in the 53rd and 54th parliaments

616
00:26:18.325 --> 00:26:22.465
and see some figures on page 31 of the submission, 153

617
00:26:22.975 --> 00:26:25.025
amendment papers of supplementary order papers

618
00:26:25.025 --> 00:26:26.145
were lodged by ministers.

619
00:26:26.395 --> 00:26:29.185
57% were released, uh, one day or less

620
00:26:29.185 --> 00:26:32.145
before the committee began, 11 outta the 17

621
00:26:32.295 --> 00:26:33.465
that were so substantive.

622
00:26:33.465 --> 00:26:35.105
They required a regulatory impact statement,

623
00:26:35.375 --> 00:26:38.305
were released one day or less before the committee began,

624
00:26:39.365 --> 00:26:41.945
and 38 of them that were 10 pages or longer,

625
00:26:42.085 --> 00:26:44.485
or in some cases a full revision tracked bill

626
00:26:44.985 --> 00:26:49.685
and were released one day or or less, uh, excuse me,

627
00:26:49.705 --> 00:26:50.925
before the committee began.

628
00:26:52.135 --> 00:26:56.625
It's problematic because it is, uh, difficult for members

629
00:26:56.725 --> 00:26:58.225
to prepare for committee for whole house

630
00:26:58.275 --> 00:26:59.945
where they're asked substantive amendments,

631
00:27:00.205 --> 00:27:02.185
not only in terms of preparing debate,

632
00:27:02.485 --> 00:27:05.025
but also preparing their own amendments if they dunno

633
00:27:05.025 --> 00:27:06.545
what the minister's amendments are going to be.

634
00:27:07.995 --> 00:27:09.495
So it would be possible to put some sort

635
00:27:09.495 --> 00:27:12.575
of minimum notice period, um, on, on the lodging

636
00:27:12.575 --> 00:27:15.655
of amendment papers that was considered in 2017, uh,

637
00:27:15.655 --> 00:27:17.495
by the standing Orders Committee suggested to trial,

638
00:27:17.495 --> 00:27:19.255
but it wasn't ever actually trialed.

639
00:27:20.015 --> 00:27:22.095
I, I think rather than providing a firm deadline,

640
00:27:22.155 --> 00:27:24.055
an option would be for the chairperson again,

641
00:27:24.315 --> 00:27:25.495
to consider whether, when,

642
00:27:25.495 --> 00:27:27.455
whether you know they're gonna accept a closure or not.

643
00:27:27.955 --> 00:27:29.615
Um, when their amendments were released,

644
00:27:29.615 --> 00:27:30.655
were they released in good time

645
00:27:30.675 --> 00:27:31.815
or have they just been released

646
00:27:31.815 --> 00:27:33.415
before the committee of the whole house starts?

647
00:27:33.715 --> 00:27:35.975
And that could provide an incentive, uh,

648
00:27:36.155 --> 00:27:37.575
to, to release them earlier.

649
00:27:37.795 --> 00:27:41.575
Mm-hmm. The final part of my submission, um,

650
00:27:42.305 --> 00:27:44.695
looks at the select committee structure and membership,

651
00:27:44.695 --> 00:27:46.455
because that is all part of the picture

652
00:27:46.515 --> 00:27:48.135
of the pressures on the legislative system.

653
00:27:48.595 --> 00:27:49.815
And I'm just say, to start with,

654
00:27:49.815 --> 00:27:51.695
this year marks the 40th anniversary

655
00:27:52.035 --> 00:27:54.015
of subject select committees as we know them today,

656
00:27:54.015 --> 00:27:55.415
they were introduced in 1985,

657
00:27:55.875 --> 00:27:58.255
and I think it's a model that served us really well.

658
00:27:58.475 --> 00:28:01.855
Um, it's not a universal one throughout Westminster derived

659
00:28:01.855 --> 00:28:03.775
parliaments, but a really big advantage

660
00:28:03.835 --> 00:28:05.935
of multifunctional select committees that deal

661
00:28:05.935 --> 00:28:08.455
with all business in a subject area is the expertise

662
00:28:08.455 --> 00:28:11.335
that members can develop in that particular subject area.

663
00:28:12.975 --> 00:28:14.655
Occasionally the subject areas are reorganized.

664
00:28:14.655 --> 00:28:16.655
The last significant time was 2017.

665
00:28:17.035 --> 00:28:19.335
The number of committees were reduced from 13 to 12.

666
00:28:20.035 --> 00:28:22.775
Um, and there was a second part of that reform

667
00:28:22.775 --> 00:28:24.615
that was proposed but didn't eventuate,

668
00:28:24.825 --> 00:28:26.535
which was a suggestion that the number

669
00:28:26.535 --> 00:28:28.575
of members on each select committee should

670
00:28:28.575 --> 00:28:30.535
reduce, uh, to seven.

671
00:28:31.235 --> 00:28:34.335
Um, one of the other, uh, I think,

672
00:28:34.335 --> 00:28:36.935
important achievements there have been is the establishing

673
00:28:36.935 --> 00:28:38.735
of a specialist committee to deal with petitions.

674
00:28:38.735 --> 00:28:40.735
The petitions committee has led to

675
00:28:41.645 --> 00:28:43.655
much greater attention being given to petitions,

676
00:28:43.655 --> 00:28:45.175
and I think a greater level of satisfaction

677
00:28:45.175 --> 00:28:46.775
amongst petitioners that they're, you know,

678
00:28:46.775 --> 00:28:48.135
that the issues they've brought

679
00:28:48.135 --> 00:28:49.335
to Parliament are getting attention.

680
00:28:49.995 --> 00:28:51.655
Um, I think the fundamen,

681
00:28:51.875 --> 00:28:55.095
the Select committee system is fundamentally sound one, um,

682
00:28:55.515 --> 00:28:57.135
but there are some adjustments that are needed,

683
00:28:57.155 --> 00:28:59.215
so select committees can properly carry out their role.

684
00:28:59.555 --> 00:29:03.135
So I think it's worth revisiting the size of committees.

685
00:29:03.135 --> 00:29:05.495
I think the number of committees is probably fine, number

686
00:29:05.495 --> 00:29:07.415
of subject committees, but, um,

687
00:29:07.555 --> 00:29:09.015
and I think it is worth considering the

688
00:29:09.015 --> 00:29:10.095
number of members on each one.

689
00:29:10.515 --> 00:29:14.455
So currently there's 103 seats on the 12 subject committees.

690
00:29:14.595 --> 00:29:16.575
So the average membership is 8.6.

691
00:29:17.675 --> 00:29:21.975
Um, as I said, the 2017 review, uh, recommended an average

692
00:29:21.995 --> 00:29:24.655
of seven members, so there'd be 84 seats on subject

693
00:29:24.655 --> 00:29:26.495
committees, which is a reduction of 19.

694
00:29:27.275 --> 00:29:29.215
Um, I think the advantages of that, it would mean

695
00:29:29.215 --> 00:29:31.335
that most members would only be on one committee,

696
00:29:31.755 --> 00:29:32.975
and that's probably an advantage.

697
00:29:32.995 --> 00:29:36.335
It would mostly be enjoyed by back bench government members

698
00:29:36.395 --> 00:29:38.335
who are a, a smaller cohort, um,

699
00:29:38.335 --> 00:29:40.455
because of the number of members of the executive

700
00:29:40.455 --> 00:29:42.080
who don't serve on committees.

701
00:29:42.665 --> 00:29:45.285
Um, that in turn would, you know, enhance the ability

702
00:29:45.285 --> 00:29:47.805
to keep on top of papers, to be able to devote more time,

703
00:29:48.225 --> 00:29:51.005
uh, to hearings, to nip not have to be in two places at once

704
00:29:51.025 --> 00:29:53.405
or rush from one meeting to another.

705
00:29:53.985 --> 00:29:56.965
Uh, the 2020 review also suggested the same thing,

706
00:29:57.305 --> 00:29:59.685
but it didn't eventuate when the tech came time

707
00:29:59.685 --> 00:30:02.005
for the business committee to establish committees

708
00:30:02.005 --> 00:30:04.765
and populate them, recognizing the negotiation that happened

709
00:30:04.765 --> 00:30:05.805
between parties beforehand.

710
00:30:06.695 --> 00:30:09.085
Committees returned to being pretty much the same size.

711
00:30:10.065 --> 00:30:12.245
And I think one of the concerns could be that that's going

712
00:30:12.245 --> 00:30:14.925
to leave back bench members with nothing

713
00:30:14.925 --> 00:30:16.165
to do if they're not on a committee.

714
00:30:16.685 --> 00:30:18.005
I don't think that's gonna be the case,

715
00:30:18.005 --> 00:30:20.645
because there are two specialist committees that meet on,

716
00:30:20.645 --> 00:30:23.405
on the same sort of frequency as subject committees,

717
00:30:23.555 --> 00:30:24.605
regulations, review,

718
00:30:24.625 --> 00:30:27.405
and petitions, both small committees, um, you know,

719
00:30:27.405 --> 00:30:28.485
meet every week as well.

720
00:30:28.585 --> 00:30:31.245
And, and there is work to be done, uh, on those.

721
00:30:31.705 --> 00:30:33.165
I'm also gonna suggest the creation

722
00:30:33.165 --> 00:30:34.245
of another specialist committee,

723
00:30:34.485 --> 00:30:37.005
a legislative scrutiny committee, um,

724
00:30:37.005 --> 00:30:38.325
which I'll, I'll come to in a moment.

725
00:30:44.175 --> 00:30:45.195
The number of submissions

726
00:30:45.195 --> 00:30:48.635
that committees have received has increased enormously,

727
00:30:48.695 --> 00:30:50.555
and that is no doubt a, you know,

728
00:30:51.355 --> 00:30:53.395
a big influence on, uh, on workload.

729
00:30:53.825 --> 00:30:57.435
There's a, a graph on page 36, um, at the top,

730
00:30:57.435 --> 00:30:59.315
they're showing, uh, the number of submissions,

731
00:30:59.315 --> 00:31:01.915
and you can see that it's kind of doubled

732
00:31:01.915 --> 00:31:03.355
or more over the last few parliaments.

733
00:31:03.795 --> 00:31:05.595
I can update that a little bit based, uh,

734
00:31:05.985 --> 00:31:09.355
from when these figures were done in, um, 15 September.

735
00:31:09.855 --> 00:31:12.635
So since 1996, uh, to now.

736
00:31:12.975 --> 00:31:14.355
So since the start of MNP,

737
00:31:14.405 --> 00:31:16.075
there have been about 1.3 million

738
00:31:16.075 --> 00:31:17.475
submissions made to committees.

739
00:31:17.975 --> 00:31:20.475
And this parliament, more than 600,000

740
00:31:20.475 --> 00:31:22.275
of those submissions have been made this parliament's,

741
00:31:22.275 --> 00:31:23.555
you know, as you know, two years old.

742
00:31:24.095 --> 00:31:26.075
So nearly half of all submissions have been

743
00:31:26.275 --> 00:31:27.355
received in this parliament.

744
00:31:27.535 --> 00:31:29.835
And it isn't just a function

745
00:31:29.855 --> 00:31:31.955
of having some controversial bills

746
00:31:31.955 --> 00:31:34.235
before the house, that always does drive up the number

747
00:31:34.235 --> 00:31:36.835
of submissions, but you can see from the second graph there,

748
00:31:37.215 --> 00:31:40.555
uh, the upper quartile of, you know, submissions that have,

749
00:31:41.375 --> 00:31:44.995
uh, had 415 submissions or more, which is a, is a lot.

750
00:31:45.415 --> 00:31:47.875
So yeah, I think there's an increasing appetite

751
00:31:47.875 --> 00:31:49.195
amongst the public to engage

752
00:31:49.195 --> 00:31:50.475
with Parliament to submit to it.

753
00:31:50.945 --> 00:31:51.955
It's a very good thing.

754
00:31:52.015 --> 00:31:55.515
And, you know, we do work to promote public engagement, um,

755
00:31:55.655 --> 00:31:56.955
and it's a good thing up to the point

756
00:31:57.065 --> 00:32:00.155
that it really affects committee's ability to do their job.

757
00:32:00.895 --> 00:32:02.595
One of the things I'm gonna suggest is

758
00:32:02.595 --> 00:32:05.275
that we look at other mechanisms for engagement,

759
00:32:05.405 --> 00:32:08.115
where people who may want to say that they oppose a bill

